#Dealing with the Senior Citizen variable
#'senior_citizen' should be a boolean object (Yes/No), not a float binary (0.0/0.1)
#'payment_method' has values with spelling errors such as "Mailed checkkk" and "Electronic chekk", which created duplicates

telecom_2$seniorcitizen[telecom_2$seniorcitizen == 0] <- "No" 
telecom_2$seniorcitizen[telecom_2$seniorcitizen == 1] <- "Yes" 

#Confirm that the unique values for senior citizen are Yes and No
unique(telecom_2$seniorcitizen)
## [1] "No"  "Yes"
# resolving the issues in the 'payment_method' variable
# - Replace 'Mailed checkkk' with 'Mailed check',
# - Replace 'Electronic checkk', 'Electronic check'
telecom_2$paymentmethod[telecom_2$paymentmethod=="Mailed checkkk"] <- "Mailed check"
telecom_2$paymentmethod[telecom_2$paymentmethod=="Electronic checkk"] <- "Electronic check"
unique(telecom_2$paymentmethod)
## [1] "Electronic check"          "Mailed check"

#We can see that there are several outliers in the 'tenure', 'monthly_charges', and 'total_charges' variables. We can remove them using the IQR method.

#Getting IQR

lower_bound_tenure <- quantile(telecom_2$tenure, 0.025)
upper_bound_tenure <- quantile(telecom_2$tenure, 0.975)
lower_bound_tenure
## 2.5% 
##    1
upper_bound_tenure
## 97.5% 
##    72
lower_bound_monthly_charges <- quantile(telecom_2$monthlycharges, 0.025)
upper_bound_monthly_charges <- quantile(telecom_2$monthlycharges, 0.975)
lower_bound_monthly_charges
## 2.5% 
## 19.4
upper_bound_monthly_charges
## 97.5% 
## 110.8
lower_bound_totalcharges <- quantile(telecom_2$totalcharges, 0.025)
upper_bound_totalcharges <- quantile(telecom_2$totalcharges, 0.975)
lower_bound_totalcharges
##   2.5% 
## 24.805
upper_bound_totalcharges
##   97.5% 
## 7565.06
#Selecting Values that are within IQR
not_outlier_values <- which(telecom_2$tenure > lower_bound_tenure & telecom_2$tenure < upper_bound_tenure)
not_outlier_values <- which(telecom_2$monthlycharges > lower_bound_monthly_charges & telecom_2$monthlycharges < upper_bound_monthly_charges)
not_outlier_values <- which(telecom_2$totalcharges > lower_bound_totalcharges & telecom_2$totalcharges < upper_bound_totalcharges)

telecom_2 <- telecom_2[not_outlier_values,]

head(telecom_2)

str(Churns)
##  'table' int [1:2(1d)] 4869 1782

##   ..$ : chr [1:2] "No" "Yes"
data <- data.frame(Churns)

data <- data %>%
  mutate(prop = Freq /sum(data$Freq) *100) %>%
  mutate(ypos = cumsum(prop)- 0.5*prop)

# Create a GGPLOT

library(ggplot2)
ggplot(data, aes(x = "", y = Freq, fill = Var1)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity",width =1,color = "white") +
  coord_polar("y",start =0) +
  theme_void()+
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  geom_text(aes(label = paste0(round(Freq/sum(Freq) * 100, 1),"%")), position = position_stack(vjust = 0.5)) +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set1")+
  labs(
    fill = "Var1", 
    title = "Customer Churn"
  )+
  theme_void()

#We see that the majority of the customers in this dataset, 73% of the customers are still subscribed to MTN while 26.6% of the customers churned.
#let's now make a comparison betweeen male and female 
# subscribers by plotting the distribution of churn by gender

Churn_Gender <- telecom_2 %>%
  select(churn,gender) %>%
  group_by(gender) %>%
  summarise( Total = n())

ggplot(Churn_Gender,aes(x= gender, y =Total)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity",fill = "#E69F00")+
  labs(
    title = "Churn By Gender", 
    x = "Gender", 
    y ="Churn"
  ) +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(color = "#0099f9", size = 10, face = "bold", hjust = 0.5), 
  )

  select(internetservice) %>%
  group_by(internetservice) %>%
  summarise( Total = n())

ggplot(Internet_Service_Frame,aes(x= Total, y = internetservice)) +
  geom_col(fill = "#E69F00")+
  labs(
    title = "Distribution of  Internet Services", 
    x = "Population", 
    y = "Internet Service"
  )+
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(color = "#0099f9", size = 10, face = "bold", hjust = 0.5), 
  ) 

#Many have fiber optic, about three quarters of the same nymber have DSL, and roughly half of that number do not have internet service.

  group_by(paperlessbilling) %>%
  summarise( Total = n())



ggplot(Paper_Less, aes(x = "", y = Total, fill = paperlessbilling)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity",width =1,color = "white") +
  coord_polar("y",start =0) +
  theme_void()+
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  geom_text(aes(label = paste0(round(Total/sum(Total) * 100, 1),"%")), position = position_stack(vjust = 0.5)) +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set1")+
  labs(
    fill = "paperlessbilling", 
    title = "Paperless Billing"
  )+
  theme_void()

Based on the results of the analysis, the following conclusions were arrived at: There is no significant difference in churn rate between male and female subscribers. So this is not an area management needs to worry about. Majority of the customers are not senior citizens so this makes this dataset biased and hard to identify whether being a senior citizen affects churn rate. Not having a partner increases the likelihood of churning. Not having dependents increases the likelihood of churning. Check on Fiber Optics. Are there some outages causing Churn? There is an opportunity to onboard more customers on Mobile segment There is an Opportunity to onobard more customers to back up solution More customers can be onboarded to security Investigate on paperless and why we have some churns

In order to create an effective customer retention program, management should take the following measures: Focus more on meeting the needs of non-senior citizens. Focus more on having customers that have partners and/or dependents since these people are less likely to churn. Alternatively, management can come up with services specifically designed for customers without parters and/or dependents. Come up with more viable products on internet Educate customers on existing products. Check on demographic distribution and how they can use this to retain More Customers Add some wireless solution to cater for segment of customers with fiber optics who are churning Add payment milestones to check on paperless payment
